Yeah, device numbers and inode numbers can only be 100% relied upon for
uniqueness if the file is still open and checked via (IO#stat /
fstat(2)).  I've never noticed it, but inode numbers can get recycled
just like PIDs (and free space) can.

Of course, there are non-Unix filesystems that are made to look like
Unix filesystems.  They still need to return inode numbers on stat(2)
and could just be any randomly assigned number that persists as long as
that inode/file is in use by a process.

And if you manage to mount the same (physical) filesystem twice
at different mount points, don't count on getting the same device
number at both mounts.




